The order of precedence between `:hover` and `:active` pseudo-classes can impact the styling of an element because they can potentially overlap and conflict with each other. This happens when you have both a `:hover` and `:active` style defined for the same element. Here's a breakdown of how the order of precedence works in this scenario:

1. `:active` styling takes precedence over `:hover` styling.

When a user clicks or taps an element that has both `:hover` and `:active` styles defined, the `:active` style will take precedence and apply first. This means that any `:active` styling will be applied during the click, even if there is a `:hover` style defined for the same element.

Once the user releases the mouse button or lifts their finger off the touch screen, the `:hover` styling will then apply to the now-unselected element. So, any `:hover` styling that is defined will come into effect.

Now, let's talk about how this overlapping and conflict of styles can impact an element's styling. In CSS, if there is any conflict in styling during the `:hover` and `:active` events, there will be a hierarchy in which the styles are applied based on their pertinence. When two different styles affect the same property in CSS, (for example, if you have both `background-color` and `background-image` assigned for the same element), the most specific one is selected by the browser, according to the rules of specificity which I mentioned in a previous article.

Meaning, all style declarations with equal specificity are applied, except the ones deemed less important due to their lower specificity. In the case of conflicting styles between `:hover` and `:active`, the browser has no way of knowing whether `:hover` or `:active` is more important, and so it may apply both on the element. But, if there is any similarity between the applied styles from both the pseudo-classes, then `:active` styling will always take precedence over `:hover` styling.

For example, let's say you defined both a `:hover` and a `:active` style for the `background-color` property like this:

```
button:hover {
  background-color: red;
}

button:active {
  background-color: blue;
}
```

During the click event, when the `:active` style takes precedence, the background color will turn blue, even if the `:hover` style is still applied at the same time.

Once the user releases the mouse button or lifts their finger off the touch screen, the `:hover` style will take over again, changing the background color back to red (assuming this is still applicable).

