There are several ways to ensure thread-safety in the HashedLinkedList data structure. Here are some possible solutions:

**1. Use the ConcurrentLinkedQueue and ConcurrentHashMap classes:** Java offers built-in concurrent data structures such as the ConcurrentLinkedQueue and ConcurrentHashMap, which provide thread-safe operations out of the box. We can replace the LinkedList and HashMap with these respective classes and still have a similar data structure:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentLinkedQueue;
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;

public class ConcurrentHashedLinkedList<T> {
    private ConcurrentHashMap<T, Node<T>> map;
    private ConcurrentLinkedQueue<T> queue;

    public ConcurrentHashedLinkedList() {
        map = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
        queue = new ConcurrentLinkedQueue<>();
    }

    public void add(T value) {
        if (!map.containsKey(value)) {
            Node<T> node = new Node<>(value);
            map.putIfAbsent(value, node);

            if (node.value != null) {
                queue.add(node.value);
            }
        }
    }

    public void remove(T value) {
        if (map.containsKey(value)) {
            Node<T> node = map.get(value);
            map.remove(value, node);

            if (node.value != null) {
                queue.remove(node.value);
            }
        }
    }

    public T get(int index) {
        T value = queue.poll();

        if (map.containsKey(value)) {
            return queue.poll();
        }

        return null;
    }

    private static class Node<T> {
        T value;

        public Node(T value) {
            this.value = value;
        }
    }
}
```

**2. Using synchronized methods/blocks:** To ensure thread-safety in a basic Java program, we can use the synchronized keyword to synchronize critical sections of code, such as add and remove operations.

```java
public synchronized void add(T value) {
    // ...
}

public synchronized void remove(T value) {
    // ...
}

public T get(int index) {
   T value = list.get(index);
    // ...
}
```

**3. Encapsulating the HashedLinkedList into a Thread-Safe utility class:** Another solution is to encapsulate the HashedLinkedList data structure implementation into a thread-safe utility class. Here's an example, with an inner class to implement a thread-safe wrapper around our data structure:

```java
public class HashedLinkedListUtility {
    private HashedLinkedList<T> hashedLinkedList;
    private Object lock = new Object();

    public HashedLinkedListUtility() {
        hashedLinkedList = new HashedLinkedList<>();
    }

    public void add(T value) {
        synchronized (lock) {
            hashedLinkedList.add(value);
        }
    }

    public void remove(T value) {
        synchronized (lock) {
            hashedLinkedList.remove(value);
        }
    }

    public T get(int index) {
        synchronized (lock) {
            T value = hashedLinkedList.get(index);
            return value;
        }
    }
}
```

Using any of these methods will allow multiple threads to safely access and manipulate the data structure without corruption. Choose the one that best fits your needs, based on the specific requirements of your project.

