Here's an example of a hook that fetches an array of objects and returns a function to start the loop:
```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

const dataframe = [
  { id: 1, name: 'John Doe', age: 32, city: 'New York' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Jane Doe', age: 27, city: 'London' },
  { id: 3, name: 'Joe Smith', age: 45, city: 'Paris' },
  // Add more data as needed
];

const fetchData = async (url) => {
  const response = await fetch(url);
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error('Network response was not ok');
  }
  return response.json();
};

const useFetchData = (url) => {
  const [data, setData] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchDataFromAPI = async () => {
      const fetchedData = await fetchData(url);
      setData((prevData) => [...prevData, ...fetchedData]);
    };

    fetchDataFromAPI();
  }, [url]);

  const startRequestsLoop = () => {
    // Loop through the data and fetch more data for each object if needed
    // For example, we can fetch more details for each person from a different endpoint
    data.forEach((person) => {
      // Modify this URL to fetch more data for the person
      const personUrl = `https://api.example.com/persons/${person.id}`;
      fetchData(personUrl);
    });
  };

  return { data, startRequestsLoop };
};

export default useFetchData;
```
This hook takes an URL as an input and fetches an array of objects from it. It then returns a `startRequestsLoop` function that you can call to start a loop of fetch requests for each object in the array. In the example above, the function fetches more details for each person from a different endpoint using their ID.

